# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: babel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] Developers can use new JavaScript language features by using Babel to convert their source code into versions of JavaScript that a Web browser can process.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] Babel can also be used to compile TypeScript into JavaScript.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] The core version of Babel was downloaded 5 million times a month in 2016, and this increased to 16 million times a week in 2019.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] Babel plugins transform syntax that is not widely supported into a backward-compatible version.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] For example, arrow functions, which are specified in ES6, are converted into regular function declarations.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] Non-standard JavaScript syntax such as JSX can also be transformed.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] Babel can automatically inject polyfills provided by core-js for support features that are missing entirely from JavaScript environments.
[src:babel/babel-transcompiler] For example, static methods such as `**Array.from**` and built-ins such as `**Promise**` are available only in ES6 and above, but they can be used in older environments if core-js is used.
[src:babel/ecmascript] ECMAScript is commonly used for client-side scripting on the World Wide Web, and is increasingly being used for server-side scripting and services using runtime environments such as Node.js, Deno and Bun.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:babel/ecmascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Ecma International's Technical Committee 39 publishes multiple standards defining JavaScript, formally known as **ECMAScript**.
[src:babel/ecmascript] These include the language syntax, semantics, libraries, and complementary technologies that support the language.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Defines the JavaScript language, formally known as ECMAScript.
[src:babel/ecmascript] ECMA-262 only specifies language syntax and the semantics of the core application programming interface (API), such as `Array`, `Function`, and `globalThis`, while valid implementations of JavaScript add their own functionality such as input/output and file system handling.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Defines the JavaScript i18n (`Intl`) APIs, and is a complement to ECMA-262.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Its functionality has been selected from that of internationalization APIs such as those of the International Components for Unicode (ICU) library of the .NET framework, or of the Java platform.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Defines the JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) syntax, a human-readable open standard file format and data interchange format.
[src:babel/ecmascript] It was derived from JavaScript, but is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Defines the Source map format, used for mapping transpiled source code back to its original sources.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The original source map format was created by Joseph Schorr for use by the Closure Inspector minification project, to enable source-level debugging of optimized JavaScript code.
[src:babel/ecmascript] In 2024, the source map format was published as an Ecma standard.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The ECMAScript specification is a standardized specification of a scripting language developed by Brendan Eich of Netscape; initially named Mocha, then LiveScript, and finally JavaScript.
[src:babel/ecmascript] In December 1995, Sun Microsystems and Netscape announced JavaScript in a press release.
[src:babel/ecmascript] In November 1996, Netscape announced a meeting of the Ecma International standards organization to advance the standardization of JavaScript.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The first edition of ECMA-262 was adopted by the Ecma General Assembly in June 1997.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Several editions of the language standard have been published since then.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The name "ECMAScript" was a compromise between the organizations involved in standardizing the language, especially Netscape and Microsoft, whose disputes dominated the early standards sessions.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Eich commented that "ECMAScript was always an unwanted trade name that sounds like a skin disease." ECMAScript has been formalized through operational semantics by work at Stanford University and the Department of Computing, Imperial College London for security analysis and standardization.
[src:babel/ecmascript] "ECMA" stood for "European Computer Manufacturers Association" until 1994.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Ecma's Technical Committee 39 (TC39) is responsible for the maintenance of ECMAScript.
[src:babel/ecmascript] New proposals to the language go through a staged process, with each stage representing the completeness of the proposal's specification.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Consensus must be reached within the committee to advance a proposal to the next stage.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Proposals that reach stage 4, the final stage, will be included into the next version of the standard.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Since the release of version 6 in June 2015, new major versions have been finalized and published every June.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The ECMAScript language includes structured, dynamic, functional, and prototype-based features.
[src:babel/ecmascript] ECMAScript JavaScript supports C-style structured programming.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Previously, JavaScript only supported function scoping using the keyword `var`, but ECMAScript 2015 added the keywords `let` and `const`, allowing JavaScript to support both block scoping and function scoping.
[src:babel/ecmascript] JavaScript supports automatic semicolon insertion, meaning that semicolons that normally terminate a statement in C may be omitted in JavaScript.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Like C-style languages, control flow is done with the `while`, `for`, `do` / `while`, `if` / `else`, and `switch` statements.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Functions are weakly typed and may accept and return any type.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Arguments not provided default to `undefined`.
[src:babel/ecmascript] This means that certain types are assigned implicitly based on the operation being performed.
[src:babel/ecmascript] However, there are several quirks in JavaScript's implementation of the conversion of a variable from one type to another.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Thus, a type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:babel/ecmascript] ECMAScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Since ES 2015, transpiling JavaScript has become very common.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Transpilation is a source-to-source compilation in which newer versions of JavaScript are used, and a transpiler rewrites the source code so that it is supported by older browsers.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Usually, transpilers transpile down to ES3 to maintain compatibility with all versions of browsers.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The settings to transpile to a specific version can be configured according to need.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Transpiling adds an extra step to the build process and is sometimes done to avoid needing polyfills.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Polyfills create new features for older environments that lack them.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Polyfills do this at runtime in the interpreter, such as the user's browser or on the server.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Instead, transpiling rewrites the ECMA code itself during the build phase of development before it reaches the interpreter.
[src:babel/ecmascript] In 2010, Ecma International started developing a standards test for Ecma 262 ECMAScript.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Test262 is an ECMAScript conformance test suite that can be used to check how closely a JavaScript implementation follows the ECMAScript Specification.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The test suite contains thousands of individual tests, each of which tests some specific requirement(s) of the ECMAScript specification.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The development of Test262 is a project of the Ecma Technical Committee 39 (TC39).
[src:babel/ecmascript] The testing framework and the individual tests are contributed to Ecma by member organizations of TC39.
[src:babel/ecmascript] Important contributions were made by Google (Sputnik test suite) and Microsoft, who both contributed thousands of tests.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The Test262 test suite consisted of 38014 tests as of January 2020.
[src:babel/ecmascript] ECMAScript specifications through ES7 are well-supported in major web browsers.
[src:babel/ecmascript] The table below shows the conformance rate for current versions of software with respect to the most recent editions of ECMAScript.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This guide gives you all you need to get started with JavaScript module syntax.
[src:babel/guide-modules] JavaScript programs started off pretty small — most of its usage in the early days was to do isolated scripting tasks, providing a bit of interactivity to your web pages where needed, so large scripts were generally not needed.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Fast forward a few years and we now have complete applications being run in browsers with a lot of JavaScript, as well as JavaScript being used in other contexts (Node.js, for example).
[src:babel/guide-modules] Complex projects necessitate a mechanism for splitting JavaScript programs into separate modules that can be imported when needed.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Node.js has had this ability for a long time, and there are a number of JavaScript libraries and frameworks that enable module usage (for example, other CommonJS and AMD-based module systems like RequireJS, webpack, and Babel).
[src:babel/guide-modules] All modern browsers support module features natively without needing transpilation.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It can only be a good thing — browsers can optimize loading of modules, making it more efficient than having to use a library and do all of that extra client-side processing and extra round trips.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It does not obsolete bundlers like webpack, though — bundlers still do a good job at partitioning code into reasonably sized chunks, and are able to do other optimizations like minification, dead code elimination, and tree-shaking.
[src:babel/guide-modules] To demonstrate usage of modules, we've created a set of examples that you can find on GitHub.
[src:babel/guide-modules] These examples demonstrate a set of modules that create a `<canvas>` element on a webpage, and then draw (and report information about) different shapes on the canvas.
[src:babel/guide-modules] These are fairly trivial, but have been kept deliberately simple to demonstrate modules clearly.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Throughout this article, we've used `.js` extensions for our module files, but in other resources you may see the `.mjs` extension used instead.
[src:babel/guide-modules] V8's documentation recommends this, for example.
[src:babel/guide-modules] However, we decided to keep using `.js`, at least for the moment.
[src:babel/guide-modules] To get modules to work correctly in a browser, you need to make sure that your server is serving them with a `Content-Type` header that contains a JavaScript MIME type such as `text/javascript`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If you don't, you'll get a strict MIME type checking error along the lines of "The server responded with a non-JavaScript MIME type" and the browser won't run your JavaScript.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Most servers already set the correct type for `.js` files, but not yet for `.mjs` files.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Servers that already serve `.mjs` files correctly include GitHub Pages and `http-server` for Node.js.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is OK if you are using such an environment already, or if you aren't but you know what you are doing and have access (i.e., you can configure your server to set the correct `Content-Type` for `.mjs` files).
[src:babel/guide-modules] It could however cause confusion if you don't control the server you are serving files from, or are publishing files for public use, as we are here.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For learning and portability purposes, we decided to keep to `.js`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If you really value the clarity of using `.mjs` for modules versus using `.js` for "normal" JavaScript files, but don't want to run into the problem described above, you could always use `.mjs` during development and convert them to `.js` during your build step.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The first thing you do to get access to module features is export them.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is done using the `export` statement.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You can export functions, `var`, `let`, `const`, and — as we'll see later — classes.
[src:babel/guide-modules] They need to be top-level items: for example, you can't use `export` inside a function.
[src:babel/guide-modules] A more convenient way of exporting all the items you want to export is to use a single export statement at the end of your module file, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to export wrapped in curly braces.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Once you've exported some features out of your module, you need to import them into your script to be able to use them.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You use the `import` statement, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to import wrapped in curly braces, followed by the keyword `from`, followed by the *module specifier*.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The *module specifier* provides a string that the JavaScript environment can resolve to a path to the module file.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In a browser, this could be a path relative to the site root, which for our `basic-modules` example would be `/js-examples/module-examples/basic-modules`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] However, here we are instead using the dot (`.`) syntax to mean "the current location", followed by the relative path to the file we are trying to find.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is much better than writing out the entire absolute path each time, as relative paths are shorter and make the URL portable — the example will still work if you move it to a different location in the site hierarchy.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You can see such lines in action in `main.js`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Once you've imported the features into your script, you can use them just like they were defined inside the same file.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Import maps allow developers to instead specify almost any text they want in the module specifier when importing a module; the map provides a corresponding value that will replace the text when the module URL is resolved.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For example, the `imports` key in the import map below defines a "module specifier map" JSON object where the property names can be used as module specifiers, and the corresponding values will be substituted when the browser resolves the module URL.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The values must be absolute or relative URLs.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Relative URLs are resolved to absolute URL addresses using the base URL of the document containing the import map.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The import map is defined using a JSON object inside a `<script>` element with the `type` attribute set to `importmap`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Note that an import map only applies to the document — the specification does not cover how to apply an import map in a worker or worklet context.
[src:babel/guide-modules] With this map you can now use the property names above as module specifiers.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If there is no trailing forward slash on the module specifier key then the whole module specifier key is matched and substituted.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For example, below we match bare module names, and remap a URL to another path.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If the module specifier has a trailing forward slash then the value must have one as well, and the key is matched as a "path prefix".
[src:babel/guide-modules] This allows remapping of whole classes of URLs.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It is possible for multiple keys in an import map to be valid matches for a module specifier.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For example, a module specifier of `shapes/circle/` could match the module specifier keys `shapes/` and `shapes/circle/`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this case the browser will select the most specific (longest) matching module specifier key.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Import maps allow modules to be imported using bare module names (as in Node.js), and can also simulate importing modules from packages, both with and without file extensions.
[src:babel/guide-modules] While not shown above, they also allow particular versions of a library to be imported, based on the path of the script that is importing the module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Generally they let developers write more ergonomic import code, and make it easier to manage the different versions and dependencies of modules used by a site.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This can reduce the effort required to use the same JavaScript libraries in both browser and server.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The following sections expand on the various features outlined above.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In some JavaScript environments, such as Node.js, you can use bare names for the module specifier.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This works because the environment can resolve module names to a standard location in the file system.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For example, you might use the following syntax to import the "square" module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] To use bare names on a browser you need an import map, which provides the information needed by the browser to resolve module specifiers to URLs (JavaScript will throw a `TypeError` if it attempts to import a module specifier that can't be resolved to a module location).
[src:babel/guide-modules] Below you can see a map that defines a `square` module specifier key, which in this case maps to a relative address value.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Module specifier map entries, where both the specifier key and its associated value have a trailing forward slash (`/`), can be used as a path-prefix.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This allows the remapping of a whole set of import URLs from one location to another.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It can also be used to emulate working with "packages and modules", such as you might see in the Node ecosystem.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It is possible to import `fp` above without the `.js` file extension, but you would need to create a bare module specifier key for that file, such as `lodash/fp`, rather than using the path.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This may be reasonable for just one module, but scales poorly if you wish to import many modules.
[src:babel/guide-modules] A module specifier key doesn't have to be path — it can also be an absolute URL (or a URL-like relative path like `./`, `../`, `/`).
[src:babel/guide-modules] This may be useful if you want to remap a module that has absolute paths to a resource with your own local resources.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Ecosystems like Node use package managers such as npm to manage modules and their dependencies.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The package manager ensures that each module is separated from other modules and their dependencies.
[src:babel/guide-modules] As a result, while a complex application might include the same module multiple times with several different versions in different parts of the module graph, users do not need to think about this complexity.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Import maps similarly allow you to have multiple versions of dependencies in your application and refer to them using the same module specifier.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You implement this with the `scopes` key, which allows you to provide module specifier maps that will be used depending on the path of the script performing the import.
[src:babel/guide-modules] With this mapping, if a script with a URL that contains `/node_modules/dependency/` imports `cool-module`, the version in `/node_modules/some/other/location/cool-module/index.js` will be used.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The map in `imports` is used as a fallback if there is no matching scope in the scoped map, or the matching scopes don't contain a matching specifier.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For example, if `cool-module` is imported from a script with a non-matching scope path, then the module specifier map in `imports` will be used instead, mapping to the version in `/node_modules/cool-module/index.js`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Note that the path used to select a scope does not affect how the address is resolved.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The value in the mapped path does not have to match the scopes path, and relative paths are still resolved to the base URL of the script that contains the import map.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Just as for module specifier maps, you can have many scope keys, and these may contain overlapping paths.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If multiple scopes match the referrer URL, then the most specific scope path is checked first (the longest scope key) for a matching specifier.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The browsers will fall back to the next most specific matching scoped path if there is no matching specifier, and so on.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If there is no matching specifier in any of the matching scopes, the browser checks for a match in the module specifier map in the `imports` key.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Script files used by websites often have hashed filenames to simplify caching.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The downside of this approach is that if a module changes, any modules that import it using its hashed filename will also need to be updated/regenerated.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This potentially results in a cascade of updates, which is wasteful of network resources.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Import maps provide a convenient solution to this problem.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Rather than depending on specific hashed filenames, applications and scripts instead depend on an un-hashed version of the module name (address).
[src:babel/guide-modules] An import map like the one below then provides a mapping to the actual script file.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If `dependency_script` changes, then its hash contained in the file name changes as well.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this case, we only need to update the import map to reflect the changed name of the module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] We don't have to update the source of any JavaScript code that depends on it, because the specifier in the import statement does not change.
[src:babel/guide-modules] One exciting feature that a unified module architecture brings is the ability to load non-JavaScript resources as modules.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For example, you can import JSON as a JavaScript object, or import CSS as a `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You must explicitly declare what kind of resource you are importing.
[src:babel/guide-modules] By default, the browser assumes that the resource is JavaScript, and will throw an error if the resolved resource is something else.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Browsers will also perform validation on the module type, and fail if, for example, `./data.json` does not resolve to a JSON file.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This ensures that you don't accidentally execute code when you just intend to import data.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Once imported successfully, you can now use the imported value as a normal JavaScript object or `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Now we just need to apply the `main.js` module to our HTML page.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is very similar to how we apply a regular script to a page, with a few notable differences.
[src:babel/guide-modules] First of all, you need to include `type="module"` in the `<script>` element, to declare this script as a module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You can only use `import` and `export` statements inside modules, not regular scripts.
[src:babel/guide-modules] An error will be thrown if your `<script>` element doesn't have the `type="module"` attribute and attempts to import other modules.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You should generally define all your modules in separate files.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Modules declared inline in HTML can only import other modules, but anything they export will not be accessible by other modules (because they don't have a URL).
[src:babel/guide-modules] Module-defined variables are scoped to the module unless explicitly attached to the global object.
[src:babel/guide-modules] On the other hand, globally-defined variables are available within the module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The page would still render `Hello`, because the global variables `text` and `document` are available in the module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The functionality we've exported so far has been comprised of **named exports** — each item (be it a function, `const`, etc.) has been referred to by its name upon export, and that name has been used to refer to it on import as well.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Let's look at an example as we explain how it works.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In our basic-modules `square.js` you can find a function called `randomSquare()` that creates a square with a random color, size, and position.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is because there is only one default export allowed per module, and we know that `randomSquare` is it.
[src:babel/guide-modules] So far, our canvas shape drawing modules seem to be working OK.
[src:babel/guide-modules] But what happens if we try to add a module that deals with drawing another shape, like a circle or triangle?
[src:babel/guide-modules] These shapes would probably have associated functions like `draw()`, `reportArea()`, etc. too; if we tried to import different functions of the same name into the same top-level module file, we'd end up with conflicts and errors.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Fortunately there are a number of ways to get around this.
[src:babel/guide-modules] We'll look at these in the following sections.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Inside your `import` and `export` statement's curly braces, you can use the keyword `as` along with a new feature name, to change the identifying name you will use for a feature inside the top-level module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In our renaming directory you'll see the same module system as in the previous example, except that we've added `circle.js` and `triangle.js` modules to draw and report on circles and triangles.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The browser would throw an error such as "SyntaxError: redeclaration of import name" (Firefox).
[src:babel/guide-modules] Note that you could solve the problem in the module files instead, e.g.
[src:babel/guide-modules] What style you use is up to you, however it arguably makes more sense to leave your module code alone, and make the changes in the imports.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This especially makes sense when you are importing from third party modules that you don't have any control over.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The above method works OK, but it's a little messy and long-winded.
[src:babel/guide-modules] An even better solution is to import each module's features inside a module object.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This grabs all the exports available inside `module.js`, and makes them available as members of an object `Module`, effectively giving it its own namespace.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If you go to our module-objects directory, you'll see the same example again, but rewritten to take advantage of this new syntax.
[src:babel/guide-modules] So you can now write the code just the same as before (as long as you include the object names where needed), and the imports are much neater.
[src:babel/guide-modules] As we hinted at earlier, you can also export and import classes; this is another option for avoiding conflicts in your code, and is especially useful if you've already got your module code written in an object-oriented style.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You can see an example of our shape drawing module rewritten with ES classes in our classes directory.
[src:babel/guide-modules] There will be times where you'll want to aggregate modules together.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You might have multiple levels of dependencies, where you want to simplify things, combining several submodules into one parent module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For an example, see our module-aggregation directory.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this example (based on our earlier classes example) we've got an extra module called `shapes.js`, which aggregates all the functionality from `circle.js`, `square.js`, and `triangle.js` together.
[src:babel/guide-modules] We've also moved our submodules inside a subdirectory inside the `modules` directory called `shapes`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In each of the submodules, the export is of the same form, e.g.
[src:babel/guide-modules] These grab the exports from the individual submodules and effectively make them available from the `shapes.js` module.
[src:babel/guide-modules] A recent addition to JavaScript modules functionality is dynamic module loading.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This allows you to dynamically load modules only when they are needed, rather than having to load everything up front.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This has some obvious performance advantages; let's read on and see how it works.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This new functionality allows you to call `import()` as a function, passing it the path to the module as a parameter.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It returns a `Promise`, which fulfills with a module object (see Creating a module object) giving you access to that object's exports.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In the dynamic-module-imports directory we've got another example based on our classes example.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This time however we are not drawing anything on the canvas when the example loads.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Instead, we include three buttons — "Circle", "Square", and "Triangle" — that, when pressed, dynamically load the required module and then use it to draw the associated shape.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this example we've only made changes to our `index.html` and `main.js` files — the module exports remain the same as before.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Note that, because the promise fulfillment returns a module object, the class is then made a subfeature of the object, hence we now need to access the constructor with `Module.` prepended to it, e.g., `Module.Square( /* … */ )`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Another advantage of dynamic imports is that they are always available, even in script environments.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Therefore, if you have an existing `<script>` tag in your HTML that doesn't have `type="module"`, you can still reuse code distributed as modules by dynamically importing it.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Top level await is a feature available within modules.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This means the `await` keyword can be used.
[src:babel/guide-modules] It allows modules to act as big asynchronous functions meaning code can be evaluated before use in parent modules, but without blocking sibling modules from loading.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You can find all the files and code described in this section within the `top-level-await` directory, which extends from the previous examples.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Then we'll create a module called `getColors.js` which uses a fetch request to load the `colors.json` file and return the data as an object.
[src:babel/guide-modules] We're using the keyword `await` before specifying the constant `colors` to export.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This means any other modules which include this one will wait until `colors` has been downloaded and parsed before using it.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is useful because the code within `main.js` won't execute until the code in `getColors.js` has run.
[src:babel/guide-modules] However it won't block other modules being loaded.
[src:babel/guide-modules] For instance our `canvas.js` module will continue to load while `colors` is being fetched.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this case, it means that the imported values are available in the module's code even before the place that declares them, and that the imported module's side effects are produced before the rest of the module's code starts running.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Still, it is considered good practice to put all your imports at the top of the code, which makes it easier to analyze dependencies.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Modules can import other modules, and those modules can import other modules, and so on.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This forms a directed graph called the "dependency graph".
[src:babel/guide-modules] In an ideal world, this graph is acyclic.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this case, the graph can be evaluated using a depth-first traversal.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Cyclic import arises if module `a` imports module `b`, but `b` directly or indirectly depends on `a`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The imported variable's value is only retrieved when the variable is actually used (hence allowing live bindings), and only if the variable remains uninitialized at that time will a `ReferenceError` be thrown.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In this example, both `a` and `b` are used asynchronously.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Therefore, at the time the module is evaluated, neither `b` nor `a` is actually read, so the rest of the code is executed as normal, and the two `export` declarations produce the values of `a` and `b`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Then, after the timeout, both `a` and `b` are available, so the two `console.log` statements also execute as normal.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is because when JavaScript evaluates `a.js`, it needs to first evaluate `b.js`, the dependency of `a.js`.
[src:babel/guide-modules] However, `b.js` uses `a`, which is not yet available.
[src:babel/guide-modules] This is because the evaluation of `b.js` completes normally, so the value of `b` is available when `a.js` is evaluated.
[src:babel/guide-modules] You should usually avoid cyclic imports in your project, because they make your code more error-prone.
[src:babel/guide-modules] However, cyclic imports can also occur if the libraries depend on each other, which is harder to fix.
[src:babel/guide-modules] The introduction of modules encourages the JavaScript ecosystem to distribute and reuse code in a modular fashion.
[src:babel/guide-modules] However, that doesn't necessarily mean a piece of JavaScript code can run in every environment.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Suppose you discovered a module that generates SHA hashes of your user's password.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Can you use it in the browser front end?
[src:babel/guide-modules] Modules still have access to global variables, as demonstrated previously.
[src:babel/guide-modules] If the module references globals like `window`, it can run in the browser, but will throw an error in your Node.js server, because `window` is not available there.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Similarly, if the code requires access to `process` to be functional, it can only be used in Node.js.
[src:babel/guide-modules] In order to maximize the reusability of a module, it is often advised to make the code "isomorphic" — that is, exhibits the same behavior in every runtime.
[src:babel/guide-modules] These practices are not unique to modules.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Still, with the trend of code reusability and modularization, you are encouraged to make your code cross-platform so that it can be enjoyed by as many people as possible.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Runtimes like Node.js are also actively implementing web APIs where possible to improve interoperability with the web.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Here are a few tips that may help you if you are having trouble getting your modules to work.
[src:babel/guide-modules] Feel free to add to the list if you discover more!
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] In software development, a **polyfill** is code that implements a new standard feature of a deployment environment within an old version of that environment that does not natively support the feature.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Most often, it refers to JavaScript code that implements an HTML5 or CSS web standard, either an established standard (supported by some browsers) on older browsers, or a proposed standard (not supported by any browsers) on existing browsers.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Polyfills are also used in PHP and Python.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Polyfills allow web developers to use an API regardless of whether or not it is supported by a browser, and usually with minimal overhead.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Typically they first check if a browser supports an API, and use it if available, otherwise using their own implementation.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Polyfills themselves use other, more supported features, and thus different polyfills may be needed for different browsers.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] The term is also used as a verb: *polyfilling* is providing a polyfill for a feature.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] The term is a neologism, coined by Remy Sharp, who required a word that meant "replicate an API using JavaScript (or Flash or whatever) if the browser doesn’t have it natively" while co-writing the book *Introducing HTML5* in 2009.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Formally, "a shim is a library that brings a new API to an older environment, using only the means of that environment." Polyfills exactly fit this definition; the term *shim* was also used for early polyfills.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] However, to Sharp *shim* connoted non-transparent APIs and workarounds, such as spacer GIFs for layout, sometimes known as `shim.gif`, and similar terms such as *progressive enhancement* and *graceful degradation* were not appropriate, so he invented a new term.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] This distinction is not drawn by other authors.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] At times various other distinctions are drawn between shims, polyfills, and fallbacks, but there are no generally accepted distinctions: most consider polyfills a form of shim.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] The term *polyfiller* is also occasionally found.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] core-js is one of the most popular JavaScript standard library polyfills.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Includes polyfills for ECMAScript up to the latest version of the standard: promises, symbols, collections, iterators, typed arrays, many other features, ECMAScript proposals, some cross-platform WHATWG / W3C features and proposals like `URL`.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] You can load only required features or use it without global namespace pollution.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It can be integrated with Babel, which allows it to automatically inject required core-js modules into your code.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] In IE versions prior to 9, unknown HTML elements like `<section>` and `<nav>` would be parsed as empty elements, breaking the page's nesting structure and making those elements impossible to style using CSS.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] One of the most widely used polyfills, html5shiv, exploits another quirk of IE to work around this bug: calling `document.createElement("tagname")` for each of the new HTML5 elements, which causes IE to parse them correctly.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It also includes basic default styling for those HTML5 elements.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Though most polyfills target out-of-date browsers, some exist to simply push modern browsers forward a little bit more.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Lea Verou's -prefix-free polyfill is such a polyfill, allowing current browsers to recognise the unprefixed versions of several CSS3 properties instead of requiring the developer to write out all the vendor prefixes.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It reads the page's stylesheets and replaces any unprefixed properties with their prefixed counterparts recognised by the current browser.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Keith Clark's Selectivizr is a popular polyfill that makes many CSS3 selectors work in IE 8 and below.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It reads the page's stylesheets looking for a number of known CSS3 selectors, then uses a JavaScript selector library to query the document for elements matching those selectors, applying the styles directly to those elements.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It supports several JavaScript selector libraries such as jQuery.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] One of the features of CSS3, Flexible Box Layout (a.k.a.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Flexbox) promises to be an extremely powerful tool for laying out interface elements.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] WebKit and Mozilla engines have supported a preliminary draft syntax for years.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Flexie implements support for that same syntax in IE and Opera.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] However, the draft spec has undergone a drastic revision to a new (and much more powerful) syntax, which is not yet supported by Flexie.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Flexie can still be used along with the old syntax, but the developer must make sure they include the new syntax for future browsers as well.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] PIE ("Progressive Internet Explorer") implements some of the most popular missing CSS3 box decoration properties in IE, including border-radius and box-shadow for IE 8 and below, and linear-gradient backgrounds for IE 9 and below.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Invoked as a HTC behavior (a proprietary IE feature), it looks for the unsupported CSS3 properties on specific elements and renders those properties using VML for IE 6–8 and SVG for IE 9.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Its rendering is mostly indistinguishable from native browser implementations and it handles dynamic DOM modification well.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Douglas Crockford originally wrote json2.js as an API for reading and writing his (then up-and-coming) JSON data format.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It became so widely used that browser vendors decided to implement its API natively and turn it into a *de facto* standard; Since json2.js now implements features native to newer browsers into older browsers, it has become a polyfill instead of a library.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] ECMAScript 5th Edition ("ES5") brings some useful new scripting features, and since they're syntactically compatible with older JavaScript engines they can mostly be polyfilled by patching methods onto built-in JS objects.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] This es5-shim polyfill does it in two parts: es5-shim.js contains those methods that can be fully polyfilled, and es5-sham.js contains partial implementations of the other methods which rely too much on the underlying engine to work accurately.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] FlashCanvas is an implementation of the HTML5 Canvas API using an Adobe Flash plug-in.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] A rare commercial polyfill, it comes in a paid version, as well as a free version, which lacks a few advanced features like shadows.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] John Dyer's MediaElement.js polyfills support for `<video>` and `<audio>` elements, including the HTML5 MediaElement API, in older browsers using Flash or Silverlight plug-ins.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] It also provides an optional media player UI for those elements, which is consistent across all browsers.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] A JavaScript library created by Andrew Betts that implemented Polyfill.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] In February 2024, the library's domain was acquired by China-based company Funnull and within a few months became part of a supply chain attack.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Authentication protocol proposed by Mozilla, failed to gain traction.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Alexander Farkas's Webshims Lib aggregates many other polyfills together into a single package and conditionally loads only those needed by the visiting browser.
[src:babel/polyfill-programming] Hyphenopoly.js enables automatic hyphenation if it is not already supported by the browser for the respective document language.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:babel/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:babel/statements-import] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:babel/statements-import] It’s been available across browsers since May 2018.
[src:babel/statements-import] The static **`import`** declaration is used to import read-only live bindings which are exported by another module.
[src:babel/statements-import] The imported bindings are called *live bindings* because they are updated by the module that exported the binding, but cannot be re-assigned by the importing module.
[src:babel/statements-import] In order to use the `import` declaration in a source file, the file must be interpreted by the runtime as a module.
[src:babel/statements-import] In HTML, this is done by adding `type="module"` to the `<script>` tag.
[src:babel/statements-import] Modules are automatically interpreted in strict mode.
[src:babel/statements-import] There is also a function-like dynamic `import()`, which does not require scripts of `type="module"`.
[src:babel/statements-import] Name that will refer to the default export from the module.
[src:babel/statements-import] Only single quoted and double quoted string literals are allowed.
[src:babel/statements-import] The evaluation of the specifier is host-specified.
[src:babel/statements-import] Most hosts align with browsers and resolve the specifiers as URLs relative to the current module URL (see `import.meta.url`).
[src:babel/statements-import] Node, bundlers, and other non-browser environments often define their own features on top of this, so you should find documentation for them to understand the exact rules.
[src:babel/statements-import] The module specifier resolution section also has more information.
[src:babel/statements-import] Name of the module object that will be used as a kind of namespace when referring to the imports.
[src:babel/statements-import] The name can be either an identifier or a string literal, depending on what `module-name` declares to export.
[src:babel/statements-import] If it is a string literal, it must be aliased to a valid identifier.
[src:babel/statements-import] Names that will refer to the named imports.
[src:babel/statements-import] The `"module-name"` may be followed by a set of import attributes, starting with the `with` keyword.
[src:babel/statements-import] `import` declarations can only be present in modules, and only at the top-level (i.e., not inside blocks, functions, etc.).
[src:babel/statements-import] If an `import` declaration is encountered in non-module contexts (for example, `<script>` tags without `type="module"`, `eval`, `new Function`, which all have "script" or "function body" as parsing goals), a `SyntaxError` is thrown.
[src:babel/statements-import] To load modules in non-module contexts, use the dynamic import syntax instead.
[src:babel/statements-import] All imported bindings cannot be in the same scope as any other declaration, including `let`, `const`, `class`, `function`, `var`, and `import` declaration.
[src:babel/statements-import] `import` declarations are designed to be syntactically rigid (for example, only string literal specifiers, only permitted at the top-level, all bindings must be identifiers), which allows modules to be statically analyzed and linked before getting evaluated.
[src:babel/statements-import] This is the key to making modules asynchronous by nature, powering features like top-level await.
[src:babel/statements-import] Below are examples to clarify the syntax.
[src:babel/statements-import] Given a value named `myExport` which has been exported from the module `my-module` either implicitly as `export * from "another.js"` or explicitly using the `export` statement, this inserts `myExport` into the current scope.
[src:babel/statements-import] You can import multiple names from the same module.
[src:babel/statements-import] You can rename an export when importing it.
[src:babel/statements-import] For example, this inserts `shortName` into the current scope.
[src:babel/statements-import] A module may also export a member as a string literal which is not a valid identifier, in which case you must alias it in order to use it in the current module.
[src:babel/statements-import] Default exports need to be imported with the corresponding default import syntax.
[src:babel/statements-import] Since the default export doesn't explicitly specify a name, you can give the identifier any name you like.
[src:babel/statements-import] It is also possible to specify a default import with namespace imports or named imports.
[src:babel/statements-import] In such cases, the default import will have to be declared first.
[src:babel/statements-import] Importing a name called `default` has the same effect as a default import.
[src:babel/statements-import] It is necessary to alias the name because `default` is a reserved word.
[src:babel/statements-import] The following code inserts `myModule` into the current scope, containing all the exports from the module located at `/modules/my-module.js`.
[src:babel/statements-import] Here, `myModule` represents a *namespace* object which contains all exports as properties.
[src:babel/statements-import] `myModule` is a sealed object with `null` prototype.
[src:babel/statements-import] The default export is available as a key called `default`.
[src:babel/statements-import] For more information, see module namespace object.
[src:babel/statements-import] Import an entire module for side effects only, without importing anything.
[src:babel/statements-import] This runs the module's global code, but doesn't actually import any values.
[src:babel/statements-import] This is often used for polyfills, which mutate the global variables.
[src:babel/statements-import] In this case, that means that the identifiers the imports introduce are available in the entire module scope, and their side effects are produced before the rest of the module's code runs.
[src:babel/statements-import] The ECMAScript specification does not define how module specifiers are resolved and leaves it to the host environment (e.g., browsers, Node.js, Deno).
[src:babel/statements-import] Browser behavior is specified by the HTML spec, and this has become the *de facto* baseline for all environments.
[src:babel/statements-import] The most notable caveat for relative specifiers, especially for people familiar with the CommonJS conventions, is that browsers forbid one specifier to implicitly resolve to many potential candidates.
[src:babel/statements-import] On the web, this is costly because if you write `import x from "./utils"`, the browser needs to send requests to `utils`, `utils/index.js`, `utils.js`, and potentially many other URLs until it finds an importable module.
[src:babel/statements-import] Therefore, in the HTML spec, the specifier by default can only be a URL resolved relative to the current module URL.
[src:babel/statements-import] You cannot omit the file extension or the `index.js` file name.
[src:babel/statements-import] This behavior has been inherited by Node's ESM implementation, but it is not a part of the ECMAScript specification.
[src:babel/statements-import] Note that this does not mean that `import x from "./utils"` never works on the web.
[src:babel/statements-import] The browser still sends a request to that URL, and if the server can respond with the correct content, the import will succeed.
[src:babel/statements-import] This requires the server to implement some custom resolution logic, because usually extension-less requests are understood as requests for HTML files.
[src:babel/statements-import] Absolute specifiers can be any kind of URL that resolve to importable source code.
[src:babel/statements-import] Bare specifiers, popularized by CommonJS, are resolved within the `node_modules` directory.
[src:babel/statements-import] For example, if you have `import x from "foo"`, then the runtime will look for the `foo` package within any `node_modules` directory in the parent directories of the current module.
[src:babel/statements-import] This behavior can be reproduced in browsers using import maps, which also enable you to customize resolution in other ways.
[src:babel/statements-import] The module resolution algorithm can also be executed programmatically using the `import.meta.resolve` function defined by the HTML spec.
[src:babel/statements-import] In this example, we create a re-usable module that exports a function to get all primes within a given range.
[src:babel/statements-import] The identifier being imported is a *live binding*, because the module exporting it may re-assign it and the imported value would change.
[src:babel/statements-import] However, the module importing it cannot re-assign it.
[src:babel/statements-import] Still, any module holding an exported object can mutate the object, and the mutated value can be observed by all other modules importing the same value.
[src:babel/statements-import] You can also observe the new value through the module namespace object.
[src:babel/statements-import] Non-JavaScript modules can also be imported using the `import` statement, but their types need to be explicitly declared using import attributes.
[src:babel/statements-import] For example, to import a JSON module, you need to specify the `type: "json"` attribute.
